<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,570,1650,1676]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Pleistocene Australian 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vigors" authorityYear="1824" box="[422,570,1650,1676]" class="Aves" family="Accipitridae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Accipitriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Accipitridae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1437,1650,2036]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Throughout most of 
<collectingCountry box="[434,540,1686,1712]" name="Australia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Australia</collectingCountry>
, the Pleistocene (2.56 Ma–11.7 Ka) epoch was marked by arid climatic conditions, with the environment dominated by grasslands, open woodland (
<bibRefCitation author="Sniderman, J. M. K. &amp; Pillans, B. &amp; O'Sullivan, P. B. &amp; Kershaw, A. P." box="[946,1196,1722,1748]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="41 - 44" refId="ref17460" refString="Sniderman, J. M. K., Pillans, B., O'Sullivan, P. B. &amp; Kershaw, A. P. (2007) Climate and vegetation in southeastern Australia respond to Southern Hemisphere insolation forcing in the late Pliocene - early Pleistocene. Geology, 35, 41 - 44. https: // doi. org / 10.1130 / G 23247 A. 1" type="journal article" year="2007">Sniderman et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
) and desert (
<bibRefCitation author="Hesse, P. P. &amp; Magee, J. W. &amp; van der Kaars, S." pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="87 - 102" refId="ref15433" refString="Hesse, P. P., Magee, J. W. &amp; van der Kaars, S. (2004) Late Quaternary environments of the Australian arid zone: a review. Quaternary International, 118 - 119, 87 - 102. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / S 1040 - 6182 (03) 00132 - 0" type="journal article" year="2004">Hesse et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
), similar to the present day. The Australian megafauna, which included at least 20 genera of large mammals, four of large birds, and three of large reptiles (
<bibRefCitation author="Wroe, S. &amp; Field, J. H. &amp; Archer, M. &amp; Grayson, D. K. &amp; Price, G. J. &amp; Louys, J. &amp; Faith, J. T. &amp; Webb, G. E. &amp; Davidson, I. &amp; Mooney, S. D." box="[667,857,1794,1820]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="8777 - 8781" refId="ref18343" refString="Wroe, S., Field, J. H., Archer, M., Grayson, D. K., Price, G. J., Louys, J., Faith, J. T., Webb, G. E., Davidson, I. &amp; Mooney, S. D. (2013) Climate change frames debate over the extinction of megafauna in Sahul (Pleistocene Australia-New Guinea). Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences, 110 (22), 8777 - 8781. https: // doi. org / 10.1073 / pnas. 1302698110" type="journal article" year="2013">Wroe et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Johnson, C. N. &amp; Dortch, J. &amp; Worthy, T. H." box="[869,1089,1794,1820]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="ref15650" refString="Johnson, C. N., Dortch, J. &amp; Worthy, T. H. (2021) Interactions with megafauna. In: The Oxford Handbook of the Archaeology of Indigenous Australia and New Guinea. Oxford University Press, Oxford. [online version] https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / oxfordhb / 9780190095611.013.10" type="book" year="2021">Johnson et al. 2021</bibRefCitation>
), inhabited these environments until most of them went extinct between 50–40 Ka (
<bibRefCitation author="Roberts, R. G. &amp; Flannery, T. F. &amp; Ayliffe, L. K. &amp; Yoshida, H. &amp; Olley, J. M. &amp; Prideaux, G. J. &amp; Laslett, G. M. &amp; Baynes, A. &amp; Smith, M. A. &amp; Jones, R. &amp; Smith, B. L." box="[729,944,1830,1856]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1888 - 1892" refId="ref17317" refString="Roberts, R. G., Flannery, T. F., Ayliffe, L. K., Yoshida, H., Olley, J. M., Prideaux, G. J., Laslett, G. M., Baynes, A., Smith, M. A., Jones, R. &amp; Smith, B. L. (2001) New ages for the last Australian megafauna: Continent-wide extinction about 46,000 years ago. Science, 292, 1888 - 1892. https: // doi. org / 10.1126 / science. 1060264" type="journal article" year="2001">Roberts et al. 2001</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="van der Kaars, S. &amp; Miller, G. H. &amp; Turney, C. S. M. &amp; Cook, E. J. &amp; Nurnberg, D. &amp; Schonfeld, J. &amp; Kershaw, A. P. &amp; Lehman, S. J." box="[955,1238,1830,1856]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref17780" refString="van der Kaars, S., Miller, G. H., Turney, C. S. M., Cook, E. J., Nurnberg, D., Schonfeld, J., Kershaw, A. P. &amp; Lehman, S. J. (2017) Humans rather than climate the primary cause of Pleistocene megafaunal extinction in Australia. Nature Communications, 8 (1), 1 - 7. https: // doi. org / 10.1038 / ncomms 14142" type="journal article" year="2017">van der Kaars et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). The raptor guild of the Pleistocene can be assumed to have comprised most of the living Australian species, with fossil material of 
<taxonomicName authority="(Latham)" authorityName="SAMA B" baseAuthorityName="Latham" baseAuthorityYear="1801" box="[151,412,1902,1928]" class="Aves" family="Accipitridae" genus="Aquila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Accipitriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="audax">
<emphasis box="[151,300,1902,1928]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aquila audax</emphasis>
(Latham)
</taxonomicName>
(Wedge- tailed Eagle) at least 500–200 Ka old (
<bibRefCitation author="Baird, R. F." box="[945,1074,1902,1928]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="809 - 870" refId="ref13937" refString="Baird, R. F. (1991) The Quaternary Avifauna of Australia. In: Vickers-Rich, P., Monahan, J. M., Baird, R. F. &amp; Rich, T. H. (Eds.), Vertebrate Palaeontology of Australasia. Pioneer Design Studio, Melbourne, pp. 809 - 870." type="book chapter" year="1991">Baird 1991</bibRefCitation>
; EKM, THW unpublished data). However, two extinct species that represent potential additional diversity have been described from this epoch; 
<taxonomicName authority="(de Vis, 1889)" baseAuthorityName="de Vis" baseAuthorityYear="1889" class="Aves" family="Accipitridae" genus="Aquila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Accipitriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="brachialis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Aquila brachialis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="de Vis, C. W." box="[329,471,1974,2000]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="55 - 58" refId="ref14755" refString="de Vis, C. W. (1889) Addition to the list of fossil birds. Proceedings of the Royal Society of Queensland, 6, 55 - 58." type="journal article" year="1889">de Vis, 1889</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<emphasis box="[533,678,1974,2000]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
“ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Vis" authorityYear="1905" box="[543,668,1974,2000]" class="Aves" genus="Taphaetus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Taphaetus</taxonomicName>
”
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="de Vis, 1905" authorityName="de Vis" authorityYear="1905" box="[685,946,1974,2001]" class="Aves" family="Ardeidae" genus="Cryptogyps" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pelecaniformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="lacertosus">
<emphasis box="[685,800,1974,2000]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">lacertosus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="de Vis, C. W." box="[806,946,1974,2001]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="3 - 25" refId="ref14833" refString="de Vis, C. W. (1905) A contribution to the knowledge of the extinct avifauna of Australia. Annals of the Queensland Museum, 6, 3 - 25." type="journal article" year="1905">de Vis, 1905</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gaff, P." box="[959,1075,1974,2000]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" refId="ref15193" refString="Gaff, P. (2002) The fossil history of the family Accipitridae in Australia. Unpublished Master of Science thesis, Monash University, Victoria, Australia. Available from: https: // scholar. archive. org / work / uk 4 xt 4 m 66 vdjrirruu 6 bxo 4 yra / access / wayback / https: // au-east. erc. monash. edu. au / fpfiles / 22806080 / GAFF 2001 _ 2002. pdf (accessed 27 June 2022)" type="url" year="2002">Gaff 2002</bibRefCitation>
unpublished thesis; 
<bibRefCitation author="Boles, W. E." box="[1303,1432,1974,2000]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="387 - 411" refId="ref14202" refString="Boles, W. E. (2006) The Avian Fossil Record of Australia: An Overview. In: Merrick, J. R., Archer, M., Hickey, G. M. &amp; Lee, M. S. Y. (Eds.), Evolution and Biogeography of Australasian Vertebrates. Auscipub, Oatlands, New South Wales, pp. 387 - 411." type="book chapter" year="2006">Boles 2006</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Boles, W. E." box="[151,210,2010,2036]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="265 - 362" refId="ref14276" refString="Boles, W. E. (2017) A Brief History of Avian Paleontology in Australia. In: Davis Jr., W. E., Boles, W. E. &amp; Recher, H. F. (Eds.), Contributions to the History of Australasian Ornithology, Vol. III. Nuttall Ornithological Club, Cambridge, Massachusetts, pp. 265 - 362." type="book chapter" year="2017">2017</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Worthy, T. H. &amp; Nguyen, J. M. T." box="[221,497,2010,2036]" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" pagination="66 - 108" refId="ref18204" refString="Worthy, T. H. &amp; Nguyen, J. M. T. (2020) An annotated checklist of the fossil birds of Australia. Transactions of the Royal Society of Australia, 144 (1), 66 - 108. https: // doi. org / 10.1080 / 03721426.2020.1756560" type="journal article" year="2020">Worthy &amp; Nguyen 2020</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
